00:42:19.541 --> 00:42:25.142
and on the ball to 3D model all the movements throughout the game? I'm pretty sure that

00:42:25.142 --> 00:42:29.302
technology is possible, but is it worth investing in at the moment? Because there's definitely

00:42:29.302 --> 00:42:33.221
motion capture, and we've talked about this with other sports analytics leaders,

00:42:33.221 --> 00:42:39.942
that's just from the video capture. Can you talk a little bit about that? Like,

00:42:39.942 --> 00:42:44.182
what is motion capture through video versus having them actually wear things?

00:42:44.981 --> 00:42:51.461
Yeah, so I will say I'm not familiar with any 3D motion capture through sensors at all, so I don't

00:42:51.461 --> 00:42:57.461
want to talk about something I don't know much about. It might exist. There's tons of 2D motion

00:42:57.461 --> 00:43:02.661
capture stuff. So there's obviously the GPS units we've talked about, and then there's also optical

00:43:02.661 --> 00:43:06.021
tracking systems where the cameras are set throughout the stadium, and they're collecting

00:43:06.021 --> 00:43:13.942
all the information from all the players and also the ball. And then what we use more often

00:43:14.021 --> 00:43:20.981
is broadcast tracking, which does the same thing but uses broadcast video. So it's basically using

00:43:20.981 --> 00:43:26.421
computer vision to track the players in the ball that are on camera. The challenge there is that

00:43:27.221 --> 00:43:33.062
in some leagues, the broadcast quality is not as good, and they have to use models to impute

00:43:33.062 --> 00:43:40.502
the off-ball players, which is a challenge for many reasons. Yeah, that's tough. Imputing is

00:43:40.502 --> 00:43:45.781
hard at all. Imputing is really hard. Coming up with what you think the data probably was when you

00:43:45.781 --> 00:43:50.901
don't have it is really tough and like fraught with problems. There was another question from

00:43:50.901 --> 00:43:54.822
Suraj that has a little asterisk, so I'm going to read it for him, which was, are there any scenarios

00:43:54.822 --> 00:44:00.901
of false positives, like when the play on the field contradicts the predictions from the data,

00:44:00.901 --> 00:44:05.781
and how do you handle that if that does happen? Yeah, I mean there's plenty of moments where that

00:44:05.781 --> 00:44:12.981
can happen. So we always try and, like every half six months, we look at our reporting and see where

00:44:12.981 --> 00:44:19.142
we were right, where we were wrong, what we might need to add to capture things. Sometimes things

00:44:19.142 --> 00:44:24.901
happen in games that are not quantifiable in data, or at least not easily. And that's why,

00:44:24.901 --> 00:44:29.942
you know, going into this, I only wanted to use data to make all of our decisions, because that's sort of

00:44:29.942 --> 00:44:35.541
how I operated in my last job. And I still live in that camp a lot of time, but I've also learned

00:44:35.541 --> 00:44:41.221
that using video analysts and using their expertise in collaboration with the data is really

00:44:41.221 --> 00:44:46.981
like where our best work is done. So it's a lot of interrogation of where those things might diverge,

00:44:46.981 --> 00:44:53.221
fixing things, seeing where things might be breaking, and also accepting that people, like

00:44:54.101 --> 00:44:59.382
everyone's best skills work together to give us that answer that we're looking for. Yeah, I like

00:44:59.382 --> 00:45:05.062
that. It's a nice little like reminder that subject matter expertise is like really, really important,

00:45:05.062 --> 00:45:11.942
and also that when you're wrong, it can be a feedback mechanism into your data to either say,

00:45:11.942 --> 00:45:16.742
okay, clearly we're not tracking all the variables that are confounding what we're predicting, or

00:45:18.021 --> 00:45:22.502
we're just not going to be able to know that. Like we're not going to be able to track that,

00:45:22.502 --> 00:45:27.942
and we have to be okay with it. Fantastic questions, Suraj. I saw you saying in the chat,

00:45:27.942 --> 00:45:31.142
