here and peek at more questions. Do you mind if I take one of the questions, Libby? Absolutely.

00:45:42.742 --> 00:45:48.421
There's one that I really like here. Someone asked how I picked the analytics stack,

00:45:48.421 --> 00:45:55.142
and I really like that question because I was in a pretty interesting situation when I joined Bay,

00:45:55.142 --> 00:46:00.582
where I joined in October, and our expansion draft where we picked players from existing

00:46:00.582 --> 00:46:05.221
teams was in December, and when I joined, we had absolutely nothing. We had no contracts signed

00:46:05.221 --> 00:46:11.702
except for one single data contract, and we were already making decisions on player transactions,

00:46:11.702 --> 00:46:17.702
which is really stressful. So I was tasked with deciding really early what that stack was going

00:46:17.702 --> 00:46:24.262
to look like, and so I did my best to try and find things that I knew were really flexible

00:46:24.262 --> 00:46:28.582
because I didn't really know how we were going to grow. So that's why we ended up with Snowflake,

00:46:28.582 --> 00:46:33.861
for example. I felt of all the warehouse solutions, that was the most flexible for what we wanted at

00:46:33.861 --> 00:46:41.382
the time, and then I also had to work really quickly to build pipelines to get this data into

00:46:41.382 --> 00:46:47.702
a workable format. So at first, I just built R pipelines, which is still great. I've worked

00:46:47.702 --> 00:46:52.582
in full R stacks for a long time, but I built everything working off of my computer. There

00:46:52.582 --> 00:47:00.421
was no orchestration. Nothing was deployed, really, and so in the second year, I was finally

00:47:00.421 --> 00:47:08.021
able to build a more coherent, error-proof tech stack using Astronomer and

00:47:08.021 --> 00:47:13.781
Python and R and a lot of different things, but the point I wanted to make here is that

00:47:14.822 --> 00:47:18.661
I worked really hard to build a flexible tech stack because I didn't know how things were

00:47:18.661 --> 00:47:22.502
going to work and also was okay with having something really crappy at first with the

00:47:22.502 --> 00:47:27.461
knowledge that I was eventually going to go back and make something more robust, and if anyone is

00:47:27.461 --> 00:47:31.942
in the situation, I highly recommend taking that approach. It's okay that things aren't perfect

00:47:31.942 --> 00:47:36.661
right away. Sometimes things just need to work. Sometimes things need to work. Sometimes

00:47:36.661 --> 00:47:42.901
you're already making decisions without any data and you need things to give you context.

00:47:43.541 --> 00:47:46.502
I love it. There was another question that was about the tech stack as well,

00:47:47.302 --> 00:47:53.702
and there was an add-on to it, which was, do you have any advice for new people learning these data

