00:51:08.501 --> 00:51:13.222
what's the most important thing you learned about communicating analytics to stakeholders?

00:51:14.501 --> 00:51:18.102
Oh, that's a good question. Players, coaches.

00:51:18.182 --> 00:51:23.222
Yeah, well I think, to me, the big thing is meeting people where they're at, right? Like,

00:51:23.222 --> 00:51:27.942
I spent the whole first six months of my job, or even more, building dashboards and reports with,

00:51:28.901 --> 00:51:31.942
and you know, I would talk to them and be like, do you understand this? And they would be like,

00:51:31.942 --> 00:51:36.582
yeah, I understand, but it turns out, like, I wasn't meeting them where they were at. I was

00:51:36.582 --> 00:51:42.661
looking at things with the total data lens, and I don't know if they were just too polite to tell me

00:51:42.661 --> 00:51:48.021
or what, but once I found out that I had to use the video to contextualize what I was doing,

00:51:48.582 --> 00:51:53.781
they opened up this, like, communication that we didn't have before. So yeah, meeting people where

00:51:53.781 --> 00:51:59.222
they're at and just working with them slowly. Eventually, hopefully, they feel confident

00:51:59.222 --> 00:52:03.942
enough to tell you when things don't make sense to them, and I make it really clear to them, like,

00:52:03.942 --> 00:52:09.222
that I am a thought partner. Like, I'm not here to be, like, the, like, nerd in the corner that's

00:52:09.222 --> 00:52:13.541
telling them what to do. Like, I want everything we do to be really collaborative and that we build

00:52:13.541 --> 00:52:17.222
together, because they also have expertise, you know? I learn a lot from them just as they learn

00:52:17.222 --> 00:52:23.541
from me. I love that. That's fantastic advice, and I second and third it. I think that making

00:52:23.541 --> 00:52:29.302
friends with the people that you are serving your insights to is really important. Yeah, just so that

00:52:29.302 --> 00:52:33.062
they understand that you're a trusted person, because when you say, does that make sense? Did

00:52:33.062 --> 00:52:36.421
you understand that? That can feel like a challenge to their intelligence, right, where they're like,

00:52:36.421 --> 00:52:41.062
oh, now I can't say no, because I'm going to feel dumb. But if you are their friend first,

00:52:41.781 --> 00:52:45.781
